I have seen the world. Not the whole, only a part. But it is enough to be keep on a micro-note, told later to ourselves. Something small to learn just as saying a word "Welcome" in other language. Here a chunky example,
<pre class="lang:default decode:true" title="Wonderful Opening">#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main() 
{
  printf("Welcome!");
  return 0;
}</pre>
Looks cool somehow, and a bit longer.

Calling <code>malloc</code> function will definitely provide <strong>legal memory area</strong> and <strong>return a pointer</strong> to the caller. And the memory will eventually 'read and writable' inside our program. Despite this, if we call a library function, other than malloc family or standard lib, some of them does return a pointer but doesn't provide writable<span style="color: #000000;">—even—readable </span>memory. Below is an example,
<pre class="lang:c decode:true" title="Unusable Memory">GKeyFile* cfg = g_key_file_new();
// ...
gboolean rc = g_key_file_load_from_file(cfg, ...);

time = g_key_file_get_integer_list (cfg, CONFIG_GROUP_APP, "ActiveTime", 
                                    &amp;size, NULL);
// The solution is doing
// : memcpy(conf-&gt;activ_time, time, size * sizeof(int));
// instead of assignment
// memcpy is part of &lt;string.h&gt;</pre>
Look at <code>time</code> variable. It contains a pointer to <code>int</code> array assigned by <code>g_key_file_get_integer_list</code>. Doing an assignment from <code>time</code> to a new array (or single variable) cause <code>Segment Fault</code> error :
<pre class="lang:c decode:true">// Attention! Segfault
// ...
int new_arr[2];
int minute;

new_arr[0] = time[0];
minute = time[1];
// ...</pre>
As I understand, above assignment copies the value of <code>time[x]</code> not the address of it. Furthermore, It is copying a value from <em>heap</em> to <em>stack, </em>and stack<em> </em>is automatically allocated.

In other side, a question came up, soundly like this, "Is the compiler though the above assignment a kind of <em>heap</em>-to-<em>heap</em> assignment? So in the end, it realized the <code>&amp;(new_arr)</code> or <code>&amp;(minute)</code> isn't legalized on <em>heap</em>?" If that's the case, legalizing mem area on heap for <code>new_array</code> or <code>minute</code> will solve this <code>Segment Fault</code>.
<h2>Solve Effort</h2>
After trying to make it works and actually still doesn't work, here the effort list.
<pre class="lang:c decode:true">gint* hour = malloc(sizeof(gint));
// ...
time = g_key_file_get_integer_list (cfg, CONFIG_GROUP_APP, "ActiveTime", 
                                    &amp;size, NULL);
hour[0] = time[0];</pre>
<pre class="lang:c decode:true">(*hour) = time[0];</pre>
Assignment, in any way, doesn't work.
<pre class="lang:c decode:true">printf("%i", time[0]);</pre>
And the worst—but provide a good proof that it is unreadable memory—<code>printf()</code> function doesn't work on it.

All of it, cause
<pre class="lang:c decode:true ">$ ./main
Gtk-Message: Failed to load module "canberra-gtk-module"
Segmentation fault (core dumped)</pre>

A simple benchmark of C language to consider in algorithm implementation.
<h2>Source</h2>
<h3>Multiple Single-level <code>if</code></h3>
<pre class="lang:c decode:true" title="if-if source">#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

int main (int argc, char* argv[]) 
{
	int arg = atoi(argv[1]);
	int prim = arg % 2;

	if(prim == 0) {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	}

	if(prim == 1) {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	}
	return 0;
}</pre>
<h3> Chaining <code>if-else</code></h3>
<pre class="lang:c decode:true" title="if-else">#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

int main (int argc, char* argv[]) 
{
	int arg = atoi(argv[1]);
	int prim = arg % 2;

	if(prim == 0) {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	} else if(prim == 1) {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	} else {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	}
	return 0;
}</pre>
<h3>Switcher <code>switch-case</code></h3>
<pre class="lang:c decode:true" title="switch-case">#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

int main (int argc, char* argv[]) 
{
	int arg = atoi(argv[1]);
	int prim = arg % 2;

	switch(prim) {
	case 0 : {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
		break;
	}
	case 1 : {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
		break;
	}
	default: {
		printf("%i-%i:", arg, prim);
	}
	}

	return 0;
}</pre>
<h2>Terminal <code>time</code> Benchmark</h2>
<h3>Test Script</h3>
For easier testing, I've made a script for it.
<pre class="lang:sh decode:true" title="testscript">#!/bin/bash

make

echo "[ifif Code]"
time for i in {1..10000}; 
do 
	./ifif $i &gt; /dev/null; 
done;
echo ""

echo "[ifelse Code]"
time for i in {1..10000}; 
do 
	./ifelse $i &gt; /dev/null; 
done;
echo ""

echo "[switchcase Code]"
time for i in {1..10000}; 
do 
	./switchcase $i &gt; /dev/null; 
done;
echo ""

read -p "Enter to continue.."

exit 0</pre>
